Not course staff, but this class is very different from 170.

The syllabus does look like it covers most algorithms that you'll need for SWE internships, but it looks very applied (leetcode is the hw assignments). Also note that this is a DeCal.

170 is a great course that I would highly recommend if you want to gain experience with Algorithms. I do not think that this course is a suitable replacement for 170, nor do I think the DeCal instructors would endorse this course as a replacement for 170.

Hi! Course staff here. Like anonymous beaker mentioned above, we are *not* trying to replace 170 in any way and we highly recommend taking 170 to gain a deeper knowledge of algorithms. Our decal is intended for people who want to apply their algorithms knowledge in a more practical way, as well as gain the skills necessary to do well in coding interviews.

history.content:
Coming in Spring 2021:

Feeling intimidated by all the FAANG interns on LinkedIn? Stressed by the recruiting process and not sure where to get good information? Introduction to Algorithmic Thinking is the Decal for you! 

Coding interviews often require a skill set that is not fully covered by the undergraduate CS curriculum. Rather than leave students to learn these skills on their own, Introduction to Algorithmic Thinking attempts to bridge the gap between traditional computer science coursework and the industry recruiting process. With mock interviews and practice problems curated by frequency, Introduction to Algorithmic Thinking provides a hands on and practical approach to learning how to code algorithms commonly seen in software engineering interviews.

The decal will involve lectures, practice problems, mock interviews with peers, and some special speakers (JomaTech, Clément Mihailescu, and Jelani Nelson)! Our course staff has received offers from Facebook, Bloomberg, DE Shaw, Bridgewater, etc. and will hold office hours and be there to help you!

If you're interested, fill out this form: https://tinyurl.com/leetcode101

Course Syllabus:

Introduction-to-Algorithmic-Thinking-Syllabus.pdf

- Michael and Kathy (course facilitators)
